    "Background": {
      "text": "Superficial linear tear of anal canal from at/below dentate line to anal verge\nMay be due to passage of hard stool, frequent diarrhea, or abuse\nMost common cause of painful rectal bleeding\nIn >90% of cases anal fissures occur in the midline posteriorly\nNon-healing fissure or one not located in midline suggests alternative diagnosis (e.g. Crohn's, malignancy)",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Findings": {
      "text": "Acute sharp, cutting pain most severe during and immediately after bowel movement\nSubsides between bowel movements (distinguishes fissure from other anorectal disease)\nBright red\nrectal bleeding\n, small in quantity (usually noticed only on toilet paper)\nLateral to anus often indicates associated systemic illness such as\nCrohn's\n,\nHIV\n,\nleukemia\n,\nTB\n,\nsyphilis",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
